# 02 - Any Run ClickFix + Email

## Intro

We will use an Any Run blog as an intel lead. We will use the explained behavior to create an Any Run Submission filter. We will identify a submission, find the pattern, action the pattern, and validate the pattern.

## Intel Lead

Skim the following Any Run blog [https://any.run/cybersecurity-blog/new-malware-tactics/](https://any.run/cybersecurity-blog/new-malware-tactics/). Note "The attack typically begins with phishing emails or compromised websites that present users with seemingly legitimate verification processes." We should be able to find this with a simple Any Run Submission Filter.

## Any Run Submission Filter

## Identify the pattern

Next, look it up in VirusTotal. Check the relations tab to view the IP that it was observed resolving to. In the snip below we can see it was observed resolving to 45.144.53[.]213.

https://www.virustotal.com/gui/domain/bkxvnx.com/relations

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Click the IP address link to go to the VT result for the IP address. Check the relations tab to see the most recent Passive DNS Replication was bokverviol[.]com. See the snip below.

https://www.virustotal.com/gui/ip-address/45.144.53.213/relations

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Action the Pattern

Next, let's consider what we know. The ClickFix command is meant to be ran from PowerShell. The TA may filter for that specific User-Agent header. Spoiler alert - they do. I used a custom User Agent for the urlscan scan task, and it was successful. Go to https://urlscan.io to follow the steps. In the snip below I show the scan task configs. Enter the domain, click the options button, and use the custom user agent string pasted below. See the snip below to see what it looks like.

Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Microsoft Windows 10.0. 15063; en-US) PowerShell/6.0.0

![](data:image/png;base64,)

View the result here: https://urlscan.io/result/019a32f4-982d-723c-97e1-5b36f9c4b3e2/. In the snip below, we can see that the request was redirected to the /go/up.txt route. Also, in the tiny Screenshot image, we can see it appears to be code. We'll check out the code next.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Validate the Pattern

Click the HTTP transactions tab to go here: https://urlscan.io/result/019a32f4-982d-723c-97e1-5b36f9c4b3e2/#transactions. Next, click the show response button for the up.txt request to view the code. See the snip below to see what the button looks like.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

After you click the Show response button, it will lead you to here: https://urlscan.io/responses/6377bbffe246a637dd83de397dbd2ba0259f68b0e65553d93a63a3a3d8b659f2/

It will get executed as an HTML Application, so the top part masquerades as a legitimate HTML file as if it's a benign web page. See the snip below.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The malicious activities begin a bit below. See the snip below. There's a lot going on. The main part is that it is a VBScript that will execute PowerShell. It will download and execute "hxxps[:]bokverviol[.]com/go/conf35.exe".

![](data:image/png;base64,)

This is good enough for now. We have validated that the IP address 45.144.53[.]213 is a good pivot. We can find the latest domain that it resolves to in VT. We can run a urlscan task with a custom user agent. PowerShell user agent.

## Summary

We took the Any Run blog as an intel lead. We identified the behavior of ClickFix delivered via MalSpam. We created an Any Run Submission filter to find matching submissions. We reviewed the submission, and extracted the domain indicator. We identified that the IP address the indicator resolved to is being reused for the campaigns. We used the most recent domain that uses the IP, and crafted a custom urlscan scan task that uses a PowerShell User Agent string. We viewed the response and identified it is malicious code that continues the attack chain.

We identify that we can monitor the IP address for upcoming domains that will resolve to it. We can monitor the attack chain absent of the MalSpam emails.
